Raw dev notes -- RAG Pipeline: Backups, WhatsApp, and the Never-Ending Data Mess

Man, this RAG knowledge base pipeline project is really starting to feel like it's got legs. The whole idea behind it is to build a personal "second brain" – a system where I can dump all sorts of information, from articles I read to personal notes and conversations, and then query it naturally using LLMs. The goal is to make all that scattered knowledge actually useful and retrievable, rather than just sitting in silos.

This past week or so has been a mix of maintenance and tackling some big new features. The core system has been chugging along nicely, doing its regular syncs of existing data sources – pulling in new posts and updating comments. It's good to see that foundational piece is stable and just doing its thing in the background.

The first big chunk of work was around backups. I finally got around to implementing a proper Google Drive backup for the main knowledge base bundle. Initially, I just mirrored the whole thing, which was fine for a first pass, but I quickly realized that was going to be a storage and bandwidth hog. So, I iterated on that pretty fast, switching to a single rolling zip file. The real win there was adding the "skip-on-unchanged" logic. It feels so much more robust now, knowing it's only uploading if there's actually new data. It's a small optimization, but it makes a huge difference in terms of efficiency and not hitting API limits unnecessarily.

Then came the beast: WhatsApp ingestion. This was a whole new level of data wrangling. Getting the data out of WhatsApp is already a manual process, and then trying to parse and clean it for RAG? Ugh. I started tackling a specific chunk, `chunk_025`, which was a beast in itself. It's always a battle with character encodings, weird line breaks, and just generally inconsistent formatting. You think you've got a parser that handles everything, and then you hit one message that breaks it all. It's a slow, painstaking process of trial and error, fixing regexes, and trying to normalize the text so it's actually useful for embedding.

Honestly, the WhatsApp part was a bit of a grind. It's not the glamorous part of building an AI system, but it's absolutely critical. If the input data is garbage, the RAG output will be garbage. It felt good to get the backup system tightened up, that was a satisfying win. The WhatsApp stuff, though, was more of a slow burn, a reminder that data engineering is often 80% of the battle. It's a good lesson in patience and persistence, and not underestimating the complexity of "just ingesting some data." Every new source brings its own unique set of headaches.

Next up: Continue refining the WhatsApp ingestion and tackle the next data chunk.
